# Acoustic beamforming drone detection with MiniDSP UMA-16V2

**The UMA-16V2 is a 4×4 rectangular microphone array — not circular — with 42mm element spacing, which limits alias-free beamforming to frequencies below ~4 kHz.** This fundamentally shapes the detection strategy: SRP-PHAT emerges as the best primary algorithm for outdoor drone DOA estimation, while frequency-selective narrowband beamforming focused on blade passage harmonics maximizes SNR. The system achieves **10–20 fps** real-time operation via a multiprocessing Python architecture using Acoular or pyroomacoustics, sounddevice for 16-channel capture, and PyQtGraph for heatmap visualization — publishing azimuth/elevation angles over ZeroMQ to a PTZ controller.

---

## 1. The UMA-16V2 is rectangular, and that changes everything

The MiniDSP UMA-16V2 uses **16 Knowles SPH1668LM4H-1 MEMS microphones** arranged in a **4×4 uniform rectangular array (URA)** with **42mm center-to-center spacing** — not a circular array as commonly assumed. The array aperture measures approximately **126mm × 126mm**.

**Spatial aliasing frequency** for 42mm spacing is `c/(2d) = 343/(2×0.042)` ≈ **4,083 Hz**. Above this frequency, grating lobes appear and beamforming results become unreliable. This means **only frequencies below ~4 kHz produce unambiguous spatial information** — a critical constraint for drone detection, where broadband rotor noise extends to 8–10 kHz.

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| **Array type** | 4×4 Uniform Rectangular Array (URA) |
| **Element spacing** | 42 mm center-to-center |
| **Aperture** | ~126 × 126 mm |
| **Spatial aliasing** | ~4,083 Hz |
| **USB protocol** | UAC2 (driverless on Linux/macOS) |
| **Sample rates** | 8–48 kHz (use 48 kHz) |
| **Bit depth** | 24-bit |
| **Channels** | 16 input |
| **Mic SNR** | 65 dB (A-weighted) |
| **Mic frequency range** | 100 Hz – 10 kHz |
| **Power** | USB bus-powered (V2) |

Acoular ships with a built-in geometry file `minidsp_uma16.xml` that maps USB channel indices to physical positions. The channel-to-position mapping follows PCB silkscreen numbering, which is **not** sequential left-to-right/top-to-bottom — always use the Acoular XML rather than assuming grid order.

### Microphone positions (4×4 grid, centered at origin)

