## 2. Algorithm comparison: SRP-PHAT wins for outdoor drone DOA

Seven beamforming algorithms were evaluated for this specific use case. The table below summarizes performance for a 16-mic rectangular array operating outdoors.

| Algorithm | Resolution (16-mic) | Compute cost | Outdoor robustness | Broadband native | Real-time feasible | Best for |
|-----------|---------------------|-------------|-------------------|-----------------|-------------------|----------|
| **DAS** | Rayleigh-limited (~45° at 4kHz) | O(M·K) — very fast | Good | Per-bin + integrate | **Yes** | Baseline, fast scanning |
| **SRP-PHAT** | Rayleigh-limited, broadband avg helps | O(P·K·L log L) — moderate | **Excellent** | **Yes** | **Yes** (with optimization) | **Primary DOA** |
| **MUSIC** | Super-resolution (<10° possible) | O(M³) per bin | Poor (wind corrupts covariance) | Per-bin only | Marginal | Tonal refinement at specific harmonics |
| **MVDR/Capon** | ~2× better than DAS | O(M³) per bin | Moderate | Per-bin | Marginal | Adaptive interference nulling |
| **Functional BF** | Slightly better than DAS; ν controls sidelobes | ~Same as DAS + eigendecomp | Good | Per-bin + integrate | **Yes** | **Visualization / clean maps** |
| **CLEAN-SC** | Deconvolved — much better than DAS | Iterative (10–100 iter) | Good | Per-bin (1/3 octave) | No | Post-processing analysis |
| **DAMAS** | Deconvolved | O(K²·N_iter) — very high | Good | Per-bin | No | Offline source mapping |

**SRP-PHAT is the recommended primary algorithm** for three reasons. First, the PHAT (Phase Transform) weighting normalizes the cross-spectrum, making it robust against spectral coloring from wind, ambient noise, and environmental effects — all critical for outdoor operation. Second, it is **inherently broadband**, summing generalized cross-correlations across all frequency bins simultaneously, which naturally exploits frequency diversity for sidelobe reduction. Third, it requires no a priori knowledge of source count (unlike MUSIC). A variant called **SRP-Harmonics** (Uluskan, 2024) concentrates computation on blade passage frequency harmonics, dramatically improving drone-specific tracking performance.

**Functional Beamforming** (Dougherty, 2014) is recommended as the secondary algorithm for visualization. By raising CSM eigenvalues to power 1/ν and the output map to power ν, sidelobes are suppressed by a factor of ν in dB. With ν=50, a −7 dB sidelobe becomes −350 dB — effectively zero. This produces dramatically cleaner heatmaps for the PTZ camera display while maintaining real-time performance comparable to DAS.

**MUSIC should be reserved as a refinement step**, applied only at specific BPF harmonics where tonal drone energy is strong. Its super-resolution capability can narrow DOA estimates to <10° even with this small array, but it degrades severely in low-SNR outdoor conditions and requires estimating the number of sources.

### Frequency strategy for the UMA-16V2

Given the 4 kHz spatial aliasing limit, use a **two-band strategy**:

- **Below 500 Hz**: No useful spatial resolution. Use spectral analysis only — detect BPF harmonics for drone presence confirmation, but do not attempt beamforming.
- **500 Hz – 4 kHz**: Primary beamforming band. Apply SRP-PHAT across this range. Higher harmonics of the BPF (2nd through 10th) fall here and provide the best combination of drone energy and spatial resolution.
- **Above 4 kHz**: Do not use for beamforming (spatial aliasing). Useful only for spectral classification features.

Use **narrowband per-frequency-bin processing with broadband integration**. This means performing STFT, applying beamforming per frequency bin, then integrating (summing) power maps across bins of interest. SRP-PHAT does this inherently. For harmonic-focused detection, weight the integration to emphasize bins near detected BPF harmonics.

